“Growin' Up In The Hood” was featured on the soundtrack for the film Boyz N The Hood which was released in July 1991. A censored version of the track was sent to radio stations.

The following week it appeared as the third track on the group’s sophomore album Straight Checkn ‘Em. The song hit #1 on the US Rap Chart that September.

songs.title: Def Wish

description.plain:
“Def Wish” is the song that – to some people – inadvertently ignited the diss war in the late 80’s between MC Eiht (representing Compton’s Most Wanted) and DJ Quik.

People misinterpreted the line, “Biting me quick will mean you get the duck sicked quick,” thinking that it was directed towards Quik’s name.

DJ Quik would later retaliate with “Real Doe,” saying:

‘Cause they know that Quik will never quit
I’m not an N.W.A., I ain’t there, I’m on my way
To the top of the tree, for C.M.W. to see

The beef would then continue for nearly 6 years.

description.plain:
“One Time Gaffled ’Em Up” is the first track off of It’s a Compton Thang, the debut album by American rap group Compton’s Most Wanted, released June 19, 1990 on Orpheus.

It talks about police corruption and its violence against black youth and samples “You Can Have Watergate, "Just Gimme Some Bucks & I’ll Be Straight” by The J.B.’s, “Nobody Move, Nobody Get Hurt” by Yellowman, “Christmas Rappin'” by Kurtis Blow, and “Children’s Story” by Slick Rick.

“One Time Gaffled ’Em Up” reached #1 on the US Rap Chart in September 1991.

description.plain:
After the relentless and unexpected release of ‘Fuck Compton’ by Tim Dog, the song made its rounds throughout the city of Compton and the general Los Angeles area, prompting several rappers to respond, aiming their disses at the city of South Bronx and Tim Dog.

CMW flips the record by cutting it into a hook in a specific style, making Tim Dog sound like he’s dissing himself, while the verse from MC Eiht acknowledges that he may be “setting fire to the fuse”, which would cause a war in hip-hop between the two coasts, which inevitably happened following the Notorious B.I.G. and 2Pac situation.

Interestingly, ‘Fuck Compton’ isn’t the first song to take the idea of dissing the city of Compton, as MobStyle’s ‘The Good, The Bad, The Ugly’ had a track called ‘Untouchable’ which has a line about “stomping suckers from Compton with one punch!” However, this line would only warrant a response from N.W.A. on their 100 Miles and Runnin' EP on a track named ‘Real Niggaz’.
